abstract: NEW ENGLAND MASSACHUSETTS: BILINGUAL EDUCATION CHALLENGE Ron Unz, the software millionaire who led successful efforts to end bilingual education in Arizona and California, announced that he planned financial support for a Massachusetts ballot initiative to replace bilingual classes. The classes now serve nearly 50,000 students with English immersion programs. Mr. Unz and his allies must collect more than 57,000 signatures to get the initiative onto the November 2002 ballot. Â Â  Carey Goldberg (NYT

abstract: Following are excerpts from the Senate debate about the use of force against Iraq, as recorded by The New York Times. The speakers included Senators Tom Daschle, Democrat of South Dakota; Richard J. Durbin, Democrat of Illinois; Phil Gramm, Republican of Texas; and John W. Warner, Republican of Virginia, Senator Daschle With this resolution we are giving the president extraordinary authority. How he exercises that authority will determine how successful any action in Iraq might be. In 1991, by the time the president's father sought Congressional support to use force against Iraq, he had secured pledges of military cooperation from nearly 40 nations and statements of support from scores of others. He had already secured the backing of the United Nations, and he had already developed a clear plan of action. In assembling that coalition, the legitimacy of our cause was affirmed. Regional stability was maintained. The risk to our soldiers was lessened. America's burden was reduced. And perhaps most importantly, Iraq was isolated.

abstract: Sajida Mubarak al-Rishawi, left, the Iraqi woman charged by the Jordanian authorities as a fourth attacker in a series of suicide bombings on three hotels in Amman last year that killed more than 60 people, pleaded not guilty in a packed courtroom in the city. Ms. Rishawi's court-appointed lawyer argued that she had been duped into the attacks. In a videotaped confession broadcast on Jordanian television just after the attacks, Ms. Rishawi, who could face the death penalty, was recorded as saying that she tried to detonate her belt in one hotel but that it failed. Her husband was among the three suicide bombers. Survivors of the attacks testified, including Ashraf al-Akhras, the groom whose wedding was bombed. He asked the court for a public hanging for Ms. Rishawi.

abstract: A court sentenced the editors of two weekly newspapers to two months in jail for harming religious feelings by reprinting offensive caricatures of the Prophet Muhammad. The lawyer for Jihad Momani, left, chief editor of Shihan, and Hashim Khalidi, chief editor of Al Mehwar, said he would appeal, and both editors were released on bail. Mr. Momani said he had printed the cartoons to show readers "the extent of the Danish offense," and Mr. Khalidi said the cartoons had appeared in his paper alongside criticism of the Danish newspaper Jyllands-Posten, which first published the cartoons.
